  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Cyprus's digital nomad visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The base requirement is €3,500/month net income from foreign sources. For families, add 20% for a spouse (€700) and 15% per child (€525). A family of four would need €5,250/month minimum. This must be stable, ongoing income—not just savings.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Cyprus part of the Schengen Zone?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Cyprus is an EU member but not part of the Schengen Zone. Your Cyprus DNV doesn't automatically allow Schengen travel. You'll need to rely on your passport's Schengen allowance (typically 90 days per 180 days) or obtain separate Schengen visas for extended travel.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family come with me on the DNV?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Spouses, partners, and underage children can accompany you. However, they cannot work in Cyprus—only the main applicant can work (remotely for foreign entities). Each family member needs their own health insurance, and income requirements increase accordingly.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What are the tax benefits for digital nomads in Cyprus?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Most newcomers qualify as non-domiciled residents for their first 17 years. Non-doms are exempt from Special Defence Contribution (SDC) on passive income like dividends, interest, and rental income. Employment income is taxed at progressive rates, but the first €19,500 is tax-free.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long can I stay on Cyprus's digital nomad visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The initial permit is for 1 year and can be renewed for up to 2 additional years, giving a maximum of 3 years total on the DNV. After that, you'd need to explore other residence options or transition to a different visa category.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need a car in Cyprus?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Public transportation in Cyprus is limited, especially outside city centers. Most digital nomads find having a car significantly improves quality of life—exploring beaches, mountain villages, and moving between cities is much easier. Budget €200-400/month for a rental, or consider buying for longer stays.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Cyprus's Digital Nomad Visa offers a compelling package for remote workers who value English-language accessibility, Mediterranean lifestyle, and favorable tax treatment. The up to 3 years duration is one of the longest among EU digital nomad visas, providing stability for building a life on the island.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The €3,500/month income requirement is higher than some alternatives, but Cyprus's non-dom tax benefits can more than offset the difference—especially for those with dividend or investment income. The English-speaking environment eliminates language barriers that complicate life in other EU countries.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The main considerations are Cyprus's position outside the Schengen Zone (limiting European travel convenience), the quota system (1,000 permits), and moderate living costs that are higher than Eastern Europe but lower than Western Europe. For established professionals earning in USD, GBP, or EUR, Cyprus offers an excellent quality of life.
